title:
Gravestone of Eunice Freeman (1791), Old Colonial Cemetery of Metuchen
Metuchen, Middlesex County, New Jersey, USA
creator: Jonathan Hand Osborn
description:
Example of Tulip motif and clover border on Gravestone of Eunice Freeman (1791), daughter of Captain Matthew Freeman and Margret Freeman. Aged 19 years. Carved (and signed) by Jonathan Hand Osborn of Scotch Plains, NJ. Osborn and his brother Henry were important cervers who worked in the style of Ebenezer Price (Veit and Nonestied 51). The stone includes poem at the bottom: "A pale consumption gave the fatal blow / The stroke was certain but the effect was slow / With wasting pains death found me long oppressed / Pitty'd my sighs and finally gave me rest." Old Colonial Cemetery of Metuchen
Metuchen, Middlesex County, New Jersey, USA

creator: William Stevens
description: Example of wigged cherub on the black slate gravestone of Ambrose Stelle (1760), Piscatawaytown Burial Ground. Carved by Newport Carver William Stevens. A member of the Stelle family moved to Newport (RI) and perhaps as a result many New Jersey stones of the Stelle family were made by Newport carvers. Ambrose was the son of Reverend Isaac Stelle and his wife Christian. Ambrose died at the age of 16. The family were originally Hugenot immigrants.

title: Header from Funeral Broadside. "An elegy in memory of the worshipful Major Thomas Leonard Esq. Of Taunton in New-England"
creator: Samuel Danforth
description: Funeral Broadside. "An elegy in memory of the worshipful Major Thomas Leonard Esq. Of Taunton in New-England: who departed this life on the 24th day of November, AnnoDomini, 1713. In the 73d year of his age. [Boston. Printed by B. Green? 1713]" (Library of Congress, Rare Book and Special Collections Division). Coffins were decorated with funerary verses composed for the deceased, and were often distributed in broadside form at major expense (Stannard THE PURITAN WAY OF DEATH 113, 117). These verses, like Mayhew’s biographies, emphasized the presence of divine Grace in the lives of dead and hence reassured the mourners that the deceased was among the saved. The broadsides were often illustrated with iconography similar to that of gravestones with death’s heads, scythes, hourglasses, and the like (Stannard THE PURITAN WAY OF DEATH 117). These icons warned the mourner of the passage of time and helped prepare him for his own meeting with death.
subject: Broadside; Momento Mori; Skeleton; Hourglass; Winged Time; Elegy; Puritan; Protestant; Funeral; 1710s
